# Mesh Ignore File
# =================
# This file tells Mesh which violations to ignore.
# Lines starting with # are comments.
#
# Pattern Formats:
# ----------------
# 1. Exact match for specific violation:
#    duplicate:validate_token
#    naming:getUserData
#    circular:module_a:module_b
#
# 2. Wildcard for all violations of a kind:
#    naming:*
#    duplicate:*
#    circular:*
#
# 3. File-scoped ignore (all violations in a file):
#    file:src/legacy/auth.py:*
#    file:vendor/*:*
#
# 4. File-scoped with specific kind:
#    file:legacy.py:naming:*
#    file:old_code.py:duplicate:*
#
# Examples:
# ---------

# Example: Legacy file exempt from naming rules
# Added: 2026-03-15 — Legacy code, will refactor later
file:src/legacy/*:naming:*

# Example: Known acceptable duplicate (different behaviour intentional)
# Added: 2026-03-15 — validate_token in handler is intentionally different
duplicate:validate_token:auth/new_handler.py

# Example: Ignore all naming violations in test files
file:tests/*:naming:*

# Example: Ignore specific circular dependency (known architectural issue)
# Added: 2026-03-15 — Will fix in next refactor
circular:auth:utils

# Example: Ignore all violations in generated code
file:generated/*:*

# Best Practices:
# ---------------
# 1. Always add a comment explaining WHY you're ignoring
# 2. Include the date when the ignore was added
# 3. Prefer file-scoped ignores over global wildcards
# 4. Review and remove ignores when technical debt is paid
# 5. Never ignore violations to make CI pass without discussion
